      "content": "If you're looking for truly radical approaches, you could investigate the doctrine of *frustration of purpose*, arguing that even if the primary contract was breached, an unforeseen event has rendered the entire benefit of the agreement pointless for the plaintiff. Another fringe angle involves challenging the *assumption of risk* if the specific harm incurred was inherently dangerous or an acknowledged peril in the contract's subject matter. These highly unconventional theories require very specific facts to succeed, but they can certainly throw opposing counsel into disarray.",
